DOCUMENT();
############################################################ # Load Macros ############################################################ loadMacros( "PGstandard.pl", "PGML.pl", "AnswerFormatHelp.pl", "PCCmacros.pl", "parserNumberWithUnits.pl", "parserLinearRelation.pl", "PGcourse.pl", ); COMMENT('Authored in PreTeXt');
############################################################ # Header ############################################################ TEXT(beginproblem());
############################################################ # PG Setup Code ############################################################ $final = random(300, 400, 10); $end = NumberWithUnits("$final gal"); $rate = random(8,12); $speed = NumberWithUnits("$rate gal/min"); $initial = random(100, 150, 10); $start = NumberWithUnits("$initial gal"); Context("LinearRelation")->variables->are(t => 'Real'); $inequality = LinearRelation("$initial + $rate t <= $final");
############################################################ # Body ############################################################
BEGIN_PGML Write an inequality to model the scenario. There is no need to solve the inequality.
A swimming pool is filling with water from a garden hose at a rate of [`[$speed]\text{.}`] If the pool already has [`[$start]`] of water and can hold up to [`[$end]\text{,}`] set up an inequality modeling how much time can pass without the pool overflowing. There is no need to solve it.
[@KeyboardInstructions('Use [|t|]* as the variable.')@]**
[_]{$inequality}{20}
END_PGML
